@Gunnar, is this code even used by you guys anymore?  Is this an opportunity to just get rid of it?
Yes, but not sure we plan to in the future. @Sunitha, what do you think about removing the locks.hpp ?

Yes. We had an agreement on this part of the code. 
1. Remove it
2. Move it to a dbus app.

Yes Ed, we will come back on this shortly after an internal conclusion on the final design. Currently this code is being used actively by IBM.
Let's comment out to get clang-tidy working and then can decide what we want to do here

It'll submit a toned down commit message + log message but with the std::terminate in place.  We can't just comment out the function because it ripples up further.  I'd rather make it obvious that the code is unable to function rather than silently failing some comparison operation.
I'm good with that.

Sunitha,

Can someone from your team please at least bring it up to the coding standard?  I have been ok with not asking for this earlier because it only effected IBM reliability in the past, but today it's causing significant thrash in upgrading compilers/tidy, because it flags so many issues that are non-trivial to fix because the code isn't clear.

Regardless of breaking this out to another dbus app, this code needs improved, or removed.

Alternatively, we can move the ibm oem code back to what we used to do, where it's not compiled unless the option is enabled so it doesn't effect anyone else, because it's effectively unmaintained, and then we can just do what we do with other platforms when they have code that doesn't compile against the latest distro release.

Hi Ed, Sure. 
Let this code be commented out to get the clang moving. One of our team members will either refactor/remove this code based on the conclusion which we will arrive this weekend.
Done

In the authors defense, I'm the one that added the NOLINTNEXTLINE, because I couldn't figure out what the heck this code was meant to be doing, and I didn't feel like touching it, given it's in the IBM oem section.
Done

The NOLINTNEXTLINE calls came later 
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/commit/ca45aa3c416e55027b8d17078bac6493e81d564f

Hi Patrick, 
Do you really want these lines to be printed in the journal traces? This is an existing master code, and any later change (clang which came in a day ago here) which comes in may need some changes in the existing code to make it compatible to the new change. That does not mean to use the kind of statements which are mentioned here. 
Please see if you can let out your concerns in a healthy way.

I don’t have time to fix everyone’s code on this project. Please suggest a reasonable fix, either in comments or by sending up your own patch set. I cannot invest the brain cells on this code to come up with one on my own because the code is not reasonable to begin with and this is IBM’s OEM code. 

If no one at IBM proposes a fix, something along these lines will be merged for the sake of the project as a whole. 

Sure, I could tone down the words here and probably will if this is what we go with.
Done
I tested this stack, it looked good. No new validator errors.
